words.meaning: (Of a person or action) innocent and unsuspecting; naive.
examples: Her ingenuous questions showed her complete lack of experience in the matter.
He had an ingenuous charm that made everyone trust him immediately.

words.meaning: (Of a habit, belief, or attitude) firmly fixed or established; difficult to change.
examples: His habit of procrastinating was deeply ingrained and hard to break.
The importance of family was ingrained in him from a young age.

words.meaning: An ungrateful person.
examples: She felt he was an ingrate for not even thanking her for the thoughtful gift.
Only an ingrate would complain about the free meal he was given.

words.meaning: To bring oneself into favor with someone by flattering or trying to please them.
examples: He tried to ingratiate himself with the new boss by agreeing with everything she said.
The new employee's attempts to ingratiate herself with her colleagues were obvious.

words.meaning: Existing in something as a permanent, essential, or characteristic attribute.
examples: There is an inherent risk involved in skydiving.
A love of music seems to be an inherent part of her personality.

words.meaning: To hinder, restrain, or prevent (an action or process).
examples: Fear of failure can inhibit people from pursuing their goals.
This new drug is designed to inhibit the growth of tumors.

words.meaning: A feeling that makes one self-conscious and unable to act in a relaxed and natural way.
examples: After a glass of wine, he lost his inhibitions and started to dance.
Her shyness and inhibitions made it difficult for her to make new friends.

words.meaning: Tending to obstruct or harm; unfriendly or hostile.
examples: The harsh new regulations were inimical to the growth of small businesses.
His inimical attitude made it clear he was not open to discussion.

words.meaning: So good or unusual as to be impossible to copy; unique.
examples: The famous actor had an inimitable style that set him apart.
She brought her own inimitable charm and wit to the role.

words.meaning: Grossly unfair and morally wrong.
examples: The country suffered under the dictator's iniquitous regime.
The protestors fought against the iniquitous system of segregation.

words.meaning: Immoral or grossly unfair behavior.
examples: The book exposed the iniquity and corruption of the city's leaders.
He decried the iniquity of the situation, where the rich got richer and the poor got poorer.

words.meaning: To cause (a process or action) to begin; to admit someone into a secret society or group.
examples: The company plans to initiate a new recycling program next month.
The new members were initiated into the club with a special ceremony.

words.meaning: A slight knowledge or suspicion; a hint.
examples: I had an inkling that he wasn't telling me the whole truth.
She had no inkling of the surprise party they were planning for her.

words.meaning: Inborn; natural.
examples: She has an innate talent for playing the piano.
Birds have an innate ability to navigate during migration.

words.meaning: To supply (an organ or other body part) with nerves.
examples: The optic nerve innervates the eye.
The surgeon was careful not to damage the nerves that innervate the hand.

words.meaning: Not harmful or offensive.
examples: It seemed like an innocuous comment, but it caused a lot of trouble.
The spider was large but completely innocuous.

words.meaning: Not harmful or offensive.
examples: The substance was tested and found to be innocuous to humans.
He made a few innocuous jokes to lighten the mood.

words.meaning: Occurring at an inconvenient or inappropriate time.
examples: His request for a raise came at an inopportune time, as the company was losing money.
The power went out at the most inopportune moment, right before the end of the movie.

words.meaning: Unusually or disproportionately large; excessive.
examples: He spent an inordinate amount of time playing video games.
The case has attracted an inordinate amount of media attention.

words.meaning: A judicial inquiry to ascertain the facts relating to an incident, such as a death.
examples: The coroner's inquest was held to determine the cause of the man's death.
An inquest into the plane crash will begin next week.

words.meaning: Having or showing an interest in learning things; curious.
examples: The inquisitive child asked his parents endless questions.
She has an inquisitive mind and loves to solve puzzles.

words.meaning: (Of an appetite or desire) impossible to satisfy.
examples: He has an insatiable appetite for knowledge and reads constantly.
Her desire for adventure was insatiable.

words.meaning: Impossible to understand or interpret.
examples: He sat silently with an inscrutable expression on his face.
Her motives for quitting her job remained inscrutable to her colleagues.

words.meaning: Without one's mental faculties, typically as a result of injury or intoxication; unaware of or indifferent to.
examples: The blow to his head knocked him insensible.
He seemed insensible to the feelings of those around him.

words.meaning: Proceeding in a gradual, subtle way, but with harmful effects.
examples: The disease has an insidious onset, with symptoms appearing very slowly.
He was a victim of an insidious plot to ruin his reputation.

words.meaning: A distinguishing mark or token of a particular office, rank, or membership; an emblem.
examples: The general's uniform was adorned with the insignia of his high rank.
Each branch of the military has its own unique insignia.

words.meaning: To suggest or hint (something bad or reprehensible) in an indirect and unpleasant way.
examples: Are you insinuating that I am lying?
He tried to insinuate himself into the group's conversation.

words.meaning: Lacking flavor; lacking vigor or interest.
examples: The soup was watery and insipid.
I nearly fell asleep during the professor's insipid lecture.

words.meaning: Rude and disrespectful behavior.
examples: The student was sent to the principal's office for his insolence.
I will not tolerate such insolence from my own children.

words.meaning: Showing a rude and arrogant lack of respect.
examples: The insolent waiter ignored our requests for water.
She gave an insolent reply to her mother's question.

words.meaning: Unable to pay debts owed.
examples: The once-thriving company was eventually declared insolvent.
After losing his job, he was worried he would become insolvent.

words.meaning: Casual lack of concern; indifference.
examples: She dismissed the serious warnings with a shrug of insouciance.
He approached the difficult exam with a surprising level of insouciance.

words.meaning: Showing a casual lack of concern; indifferent.
examples: The insouciant student seemed completely unworried about his failing grades.
She gave an insouciant toss of her hair and walked away.

words.meaning: Too extreme to bear; intolerable.
examples: His constant bragging is insufferable.
The insufferable heat made it impossible to be comfortable outdoors.

words.meaning: Ignorant of or uninterested in cultures, ideas, or peoples outside one's own experience.
examples: Living in a small, isolated village can lead to an insular perspective.
His insular views were challenged when he traveled abroad for the first time.

words.meaning: Ignorance of or lack of interest in cultures, ideas, or peoples outside one's own experience.
examples: The insularity of the community made it resistant to new ideas.
Travel is a great way to overcome one's own insularity.

words.meaning: (Of a difficulty or obstacle) impossible to overcome.
examples: The team faced what seemed like an insuperable lead in the final minutes of the game.
For the small company, the competition from the multinational corporation was an insuperable barrier.

words.meaning: A rebel or revolutionary.
examples: The government struggled to defeat the well-armed insurgents.
The insurgents launched a surprise attack on the capital city.

words.meaning: A violent uprising against an authority or government.
examples: The army was called in to put down the armed insurrection.
He was charged with treason for his role in leading the insurrection.

words.meaning: Not damaged or impaired in any way; complete.
examples: Amazingly, the fragile vase survived the earthquake intact.
He managed to keep his sense of humor intact despite the difficulties.

words.meaning: Unable to be touched or grasped; not having physical presence.
examples: A company's reputation is a valuable but intangible asset.
The museum had an intangible atmosphere of history and reverence.

words.meaning: Necessary to make a whole complete; essential or fundamental.
examples: Regular exercise is an integral part of a healthy lifestyle.
The heart is an integral organ of the circulatory system.

words.meaning: To combine (one thing) with another so that they become a whole; to bring into equal participation.
examples: The company will integrate the two departments into a single, more efficient unit.
The program helps new immigrants integrate into the community.

words.meaning: Able to be understood; comprehensible.
examples: The instructions were clear and easily intelligible.
He spoke so quickly that his words were barely intelligible.

words.meaning: Lack of moderation or self-restraint, especially in eating or drinking.
examples: The doctor warned him that his intemperance would lead to serious health problems.
He regretted his past intemperance and now lives a much healthier life.

words.meaning: Concentrated on a single area or subject or into a short time; very thorough or vigorous.
examples: She enrolled in an intensive language course to prepare for her trip.
The patient required intensive care after the major surgery.

words.meaning: To place (a corpse) in a grave or tomb, typically with funeral rites.
examples: The fallen soldier was interred with full military honors.
The ancient king was interred in a magnificent pyramid.

words.meaning: (Of two things) able to be interchanged without making any difference or without being noticed.
examples: In this context, the words 'begin' and 'start' are virtually interchangeable.
The device uses interchangeable batteries, which makes it very convenient.

words.meaning: An authoritative prohibition.
examples: The court issued an interdict to halt construction of the controversial new building.
The government imposed an interdict on the export of rare minerals.

words.meaning: To say (something) abruptly, especially as an aside or interruption.
examples: He tried to interject a question during the presentation.
'That's not what happened at all!' she interjected.

words.meaning: A person who takes part in a dialogue or conversation.
examples: The journalist was a skilled interlocutor, drawing insightful comments from the politician.
My interlocutor in the debate was well-informed and presented strong arguments.

words.meaning: A person who becomes involved in a place or situation where they are not wanted or do not belong.
examples: The locals viewed the tourists as unwelcome interlopers.
She felt like an interloper at her ex-husband's family reunion.

words.meaning: A person who acts as a link between people in order to try to bring about an agreement; a mediator.
examples: A lawyer acted as an intermediary between the two parties during the dispute.
The diplomat served as an intermediary in the peace negotiations.

words.meaning: Endless or apparently endless (often used hyperbolically).
examples: The drive through the desert seemed interminable.
We had to sit through an interminable series of speeches.

words.meaning: Occurring at irregular intervals; not continuous or steady.
examples: The weather forecast predicts intermittent rain throughout the day.
He suffers from intermittent headaches.

words.meaning: Destructive to both sides in a conflict.
examples: The political party was weakened by years of internecine strife.
The company's progress was halted by internecine battles between departments.

words.meaning: The way in which two or more things have an effect on each other.
examples: The book examines the complex interplay between genetics and environment.
The success of the project depended on the interplay of various factors.

words.meaning: To insert (something of a different nature) into something else; to estimate a value within a known range.
examples: The editor interpolated a new paragraph into the author's original text.
Scientists can interpolate the temperature for a year where no data exists.

words.meaning: A period when normal government is suspended, especially between successive reigns or regimes.
examples: During the interregnum, the country was ruled by a council of nobles.
There was a brief interregnum of chaos between the fall of the old king and the rise of the new one.

words.meaning: To ask questions of (someone, especially a suspect or a prisoner) closely, aggressively, or formally.
examples: The police will interrogate the suspect about his whereabouts on the night of the crime.
The congressional committee has the power to interrogate witnesses under oath.
